issue.title: Issue pinning large memory in C# (crash)

labels.name: feature request
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

labels.name: stale
labels.description: issues that have not been addressed in a while; categorized by a bot

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**

```
Unhandled Exception: System.OverflowException: Arithmetic operation resulted in an overflow.
   at System.IntPtr.op_Explicit(IntPtr value)
   at Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.NativeOnnxTensorMemory`1.Pin(Int32 elementIndex)
   at System.Memory`1.Pin()
```

In [this line](https://github.com/Microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/1288a8caed7f473d42a3b2cc6f9d2c31011d328d/csharp/src/Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime/NativeOnnxTensorMemory.cs#L200) the cast to (int) fails  if allocated on a high-address range (to see the issue use a large buffer to increase the chance).


**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows 10
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): nuget
- ONNX Runtime version: 0.3.0

**To Reproduce**
Pin the output tensor with large size (>2GB)

**Expected behavior**
No crash

**Additional context**
A colleague found the root cause in the process of trying to understand [this issue](https://github.com/Microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/706). 
We need to `pin` because there is no fast way to index the buffer of tensor to get one value out.

body:
According to a colleage who is an expert, this has something to do with C# ToArray optimized for ToArray because ICollection is implemented, whereas ToTensor is different.
As a result of the optimization the memory copy will be done in a single chunk, instead of a for-loop

@dashesy - as for being 60ms slower, what percentage slower is it (i.e. what it the total running time)? Are you comparing Debug build or Release build? Most performance comparisons should be on release build, with optimizations enabled.
It is 190ms vs 130ms, both release build. To try to see the difference make sure the tensor size is 1000,000 floats.

Adding to the options list above, option **6** below only takes **67 ms**, which should be close to the fastest possible. This avoids any data copies, and directly accesses the underlying pinned native memory, which you were initially trying to do. 

    var res6 = (resnov.ToArray()[0].AsTensor<float>() as DenseTensor<float>).Buffer.Span; 

The **ToDenseTensor()** method in the options below is creating a copy (is not a cast), which explains why it's slow. https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/master/src/System.Numerics.Tensors/src/System/Numerics/Tensors/Tensor.cs#L1179

Please reopen for other concerns.

issue.title: C# inference is slower than Python

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
A clear and concise description of what the bug is.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows for C#, Ubuntu16 for Python
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): pip/nuget
- ONNX Runtime version: 0.3.0
- Python version: 3.5
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): 2015

**To Reproduce**
Load an ONNX file in `onnxruntime` in Python and in C#, the inference in C# is twice slower

```python
import time
import numpy as np
import onnxruntime as rt

im = np.random.rand(1, 3, 256, 384).astype('uint8')

sess = rt.InferenceSession("model.onnx")

t0 = time.time()
output =  sess.run(['prob'], {'data': im})[0]
print (time.time() - t0)
```

I get around 0.09s (90ms) but when I load the model in ORT nuget I get about 200ms

```C#
using (var results = _session.Run(inputTensor))
{
    return new TensorArray<float>(results.First().AsEnumerable<float>().ToArray(), results.First().AsTensor<float>().Dimensions.ToArray());
}
```

`TensorArray` is a wrapper class that accepts `float` array and its dimension.

Is this behavior expected? is it `ToArray` that has overhead in C# but not in Python? 

**Expected behavior**
Minimal overhead

**Additional context**
Sent an email with a model file
